Our group of four had a dinner reservation at 8pm. The table was not ready for us for another 20 minutes so we had drinks at the bar while we waited. I had the old Cuban, which was delicious. We all ordered four courses and I got to sample everything my fiancé ordered as well. My absolute favorite of the night was actually an amuse bouche -- smoked salmon and caviar on a cracker. So much flavor! I ordered the salt cured foie gras, pan seared scallops, seared steak, and a cheese course. The foie gras was so smooth and buttery. The scallops were perfectly cooked and I really enjoyed the combination of the sweet onion and herby cilantro purée. My fiancé's risotto was really good and very filling. The lemon soufflé was also delicious, although it was dense and not airy (waiter did tell us this when we ordered), and the accompanying raspberry sorbet was perfect. Everything was good, but it wasn't mind blowing or exceptional. I was expecting more flavor from every dish. Nothing really surprised me. Steak tasted like steak, lobster like lobster, etc. I'm glad I got to experience this but I would not come back.

My husband and I were married at City Hall on a Friday afternoon, and then made our way over to Gary Danko for a special dinner. I made the dinner reservation about 7 weeks in advance of our wedding in order to ensure our date was available. I was able to request a corner table where we could sit next to each other and have more private conversation than sitting across the table from one another. [Ask for a table next to the seahorses in the corner, if this is your preference.] I eat a vegan diet, and the restaurant easily accommodated this. I was shown the options for the five course vegetarian meal, and was told which items were technically vegan, and which ones could be made vegan for me. My husband chose courses from the regular five course menu, including the cheese tray. The cheese tray is wheeled to your table on a cart and has 20+ options for you to select a few. My husband also had the risotto, horseradish crusted salmon and the beef filet, and was fully satisfied with all of these. As for me, it was wonderful to be accommodated with the vegan food options, however I've had better vegan food at restaurants that specialize in vegetarian and vegan cooking. The service was impeccable with the sommelier suggesting a bottle of wine that paired well with both of our meals, and then additional glasses of wine to go with certain courses once the first bottle was finished. Our waiter, Andrew, was personable and provided a refined balance of space and attentiveness. One of the best parts of dinner was the final dessert course, when our waiter brought out an extra plate of fruits and nuts for us to enjoy. The plate said, "Congratulations," on it with a single lit candle. The plate with pecans and jellied candies (I don't remember exactly what they were) was absolutely divine! For couples who are eloping to San Francisco, why not visit Gary Danko on your special day? We'll be dining at Gary Danko for years to come on our wedding anniversary.

They do offer valet parking...its worth the $12 they charge. The surrounding area is full of permit parking and the structures will end up costing you more. I think this definitely worth going for a special occassion or just for dinner (if you have the funds to afford it). Food is good and service is amazing, what more can you ask for?

Boyfriend knew that I was dying to come here so he surprised me to dinner on a Saturday night! Our Gary Danko experience did not disappoint and we both agree that this is by far the best fine dining/Michelin star restaurant that we've been to so far. We both ordered the three course meal for $76 each. It's actually a great price given that you can choose any three things from the menu. We opted for 2 appetizers (crab and shrimp risotto, seared tuna with lemon soy dressing), 3 main courses (bass with herb and gnocchi, scallops with pea purée, lobster with potato purée), and 1 dessert (chocolate soufflé). The lobster stood out to me the most and blew my mind away. I couldn't even talk while I was eating because it was that good. Portions are generous for a fine dining restaurant and the bill came out under $200 including a mojito they we ordered. Between the 6 courses, we both left stuffed and happy. I definitely look forward to coming back soon to try more dishes!!

An Update After 10 Years: You'd think something would have slipped, right? It couldn't possibly be as good as we remembered, right? Restaurants age, chefs lose interest (Bradley Ogden, remember us folks back in Marin when you had the Lark Creek Inn?), and times change. Also, we're older and more experienced diners that have been lucky to visit some great international locations and sample their best. Surely, we can no longer be seduced as easily, right? But there it is, just 15 miles from our front door, and it is still just simply the best restaurant. The food remains creative, outstanding and yet satisfying. You don't need to make a meal based on eating "foam" here. You don't need a server to explain to you why the dish you are about to have is so complex that even Anthony Bourdain didn't comprehend the innovative use of sea urchin as a condiment. It's real food made from the best ingredients prepared with both respect and creativity. In other words, just relax and enjoy. This isn't a test. The staff remains expert and professional while extremely friendly and flexible. Do they know every ingredient in every dish and have the ability to make recommendations without being pretentious? Yes, they do. Do they know the origin, flavor profile and texture of every one of the seemingly endless selection of cheeses on the cart? Yes, of course. Yet, they manage to impart all of their knowledge while making you feel relaxed and unrushed. The menu has a prix fixe tasting menu on one side and a very ample a la carte list of selections on the other side. We did both. I got the tasting menu to give the chef the driver's seat while my wife selected her items with the help of our server. Both are great ways to go here. I fear my descriptions of the food wouldn't do it justice. We started with an amuse bouche of fresh fig with honey and duck cracklings ("crispy bits" in my neighborhood). We had crab and lobster dishes both fresh and creative. There was a risotto dish that was silky and creamy yet still in the style of a primavera. Was it rich and sinful? Light and summary? Well...yes. My favorite dish, the oysters, were in a simple broth they referred to as a glaze, barely cooked and then topped with wonderful caviar that made every bit a burst of what's best from the ocean. There was filet of beef that came with housemade gnocci and greens served with the jus that added a nice smoky quality. After an ample cheese course selected by our server to our requested tastes and textures we had a chocolate souffle served with two sauces and a butter cake with peaches. Everything was perfect. The pace was relaxed without feeling like it was too drawn out...a feeling we've experienced in some Parisian restaurants where we wondered if a ransom note had been sent to loved ones with the terms of our return. We were actually surprised to find upon leaving that we had been there for nearly three hours. Like everything else at Gary Danko, the pace was perfect. Going for the first time and don't know what to expect? We saw people dressed in suits and others dressed in hoodies. A nice sport coat, slacks and no tie seems like the middle ground. For your budget, figure $500 a couple. That includes two glasses of wine, ample opportunities to taste chef's creations, and of course tip. If you are planning on giving the wine list a more thorough workout, then you should be ready to up your budget. The restaurant is truly worth the cost. Driving there? Valet parking is a breeze and $20. We had hoped the valet would bring us something special, but sadly he returned with the same car we had driven to the restaurant. Thank you Gary Danko for finding the key to keeping your restaurant fresh, innovative and perfect even after 10 years.

    Updated review

    An Update After 10 Years:

    You'd think something would have slipped, right? It couldn't possibly be as good as we remembered, right? Restaurants age, chefs lose interest (Bradley Ogden, remember us folks back in Marin when you had the Lark Creek Inn?), and times change. Also, we're older and more experienced diners that have been lucky to visit some great international locations and sample their best. Surely, we can no longer be seduced as easily, right?

    But there it is, just 15 miles from our front door, and it is still just simply the best restaurant. The food remains creative, outstanding and yet satisfying. You don't need to make a meal based on eating "foam" here. You don't need a server to explain to you why the dish you are about to have is so complex that even Anthony Bourdain didn't comprehend the innovative use of sea urchin as a condiment. It's real food made from the best ingredients prepared with both respect and creativity. In other words, just relax and enjoy. This isn't a test.

    The staff remains expert and professional while extremely friendly and flexible. Do they know every ingredient in every dish and have the ability to make recommendations without being pretentious? Yes, they do. Do they know the origin, flavor profile and texture of every one of the seemingly endless selection of cheeses on the cart? Yes, of course. Yet, they manage to impart all of their knowledge while making you feel relaxed and unrushed.

    The menu has a prix fixe tasting menu on one side and a very ample a la carte list of selections on the other side. We did both. I got the tasting menu to give the chef the driver's seat while my wife selected her items with the help of our server. Both are great ways to go here.

    I fear my descriptions of the food wouldn't do it justice. We started with an amuse bouche of fresh fig with honey and duck cracklings ("crispy bits" in my neighborhood). We had crab and lobster dishes both fresh and creative. There was a risotto dish that was silky and creamy yet still in the style of a primavera. Was it rich and sinful? Light and summary? Well...yes. My favorite dish, the oysters, were in a simple broth they referred to as a glaze, barely cooked and then topped with wonderful caviar that made every bit a burst of what's best from the ocean. There was filet of beef that came with housemade gnocci and greens served with the jus that added a nice smoky quality.

    After an ample cheese course selected by our server to our requested tastes and textures we had a chocolate souffle served with two sauces and a butter cake with peaches. Everything was perfect.

    The pace was relaxed without feeling like it was too drawn out...a feeling we've experienced in some Parisian restaurants where we wondered if a ransom note had been sent to loved ones with the terms of our return. We were actually surprised to find upon leaving that we had been there for nearly three hours. Like everything else at Gary Danko, the pace was perfect.

    Going for the first time and don't know what to expect? We saw people dressed in suits and others dressed in hoodies. A nice sport coat, slacks and no tie seems like the middle ground. For your budget, figure $500 a couple. That includes two glasses of wine, ample opportunities to taste chef's creations, and of course tip. If you are planning on giving the wine list a more thorough workout, then you should be ready to up your budget. The restaurant is truly worth the cost. Driving there? Valet parking is a breeze and $20. We had hoped the valet would bring us something special, but sadly he returned with the same car we had driven to the restaurant.

    Thank you Gary Danko for finding the key to keeping your restaurant fresh, innovative and perfect even after 10 years.

    I would rank Gary Danko with some of the finest restaurants I've been to in the world and certanly on par with eateries I enjoy in Yountville.

    Dear Gary Danko,

    You are an amazing restaurant.  From the fabulous presentation and taste of the food, to the elegant restaurant and incredible hospitality of the servers, you've given us a wonderful evening that made us wanting to come back for more.  

    What makes Gary Danko special: Other than the incredible food, ambiance, decor, and service, I like Gary Danko's system where you can order 3, 4, or 5 dishes of any category for a fixed price.  Since I am not much of a sweet tooth and I love seafood, I was able to order 3 seafood entrees!  Though everyone raved about the lobster which I have to disagree since it was probably my least favorite of the 3.  The sauce wasn't as dynamic as you would expect a place like Gary Danko to have, though it was still good.  

    Yelpers, I have to say that you MUST order the scallops!!! I LOVE scallops, and Gary Danko's scallops were PERFECT.  They cooked it perfectly to make the texture of the scallops just right, and the sauce complemented them amazingly that felt heaven in my mouth.  If I come to Gary Danko again, I am definitely ordering the scallops again.  It was my favorite dish of the night.  My boyfriend on the other hand, thought the oysters was the best dish.  They were very fresh and rich, topped with caviar.  I wish I had more than one piece, but my boyfriend looked like he was enjoying it too much ;) I'd recommend ordering both!

    My ratings for the dishes we had:
    Scallops 5/5
    Oysters 5/5
    Pork 4.5/5
    Sea bass 4.5/5
    Lamb 4/5
    Lobster 4/5

    Free: bison bite, unlimited bread, mini dessert samples, birthday cake for my boyfriend, and banana cake to take home!

    Also, the bathroom at Gary Danko is also beautiful.  They use nice soft towels, not napkins. Can you believe that?!

    Thank you for a wonderful and amazing night.  I would have to say this is one of the best restaurants in San Francisco.  I hope to come again!

    Sincerely,
    Raquel Y.
